<span class=dateline>September 05, 2003</span> - Our bi-weekly EQII Q&A is back for another edition! We know you'll enjoy it as always. Also keep in mind that on Monday we continue our EQII Screenshots, and next Friday is our second Lost Dungeons of Norrath Q&A session! Enjoy!<BR>
<BR>
You may comment on this article <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=55919603&replies=0">in this thread</A> on our <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/board.asp?brd=22210">EQII Board</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<CENTER><B>Ask SOE #3</B><BR>
<I>EQII Q&A With Steve Danuser</I></CENTER><BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> How important will your choice of race be to your playing experience? In terms of special abilities, restrictions, bonuses, etc.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Moorgard:</B> On the most basic level, race impacts your citizenship. Some races can only be good (and thus will be sent to Qeynos) while others can only be evil (earning a one-way ticket to Freeport). Some races are neutral, and still others can be either good or evil; these players must choose the city to which they will pledge allegiance.<BR>
<BR>
Your race also determines which sub-classes you can ultimately choose from. Just as there were certain allowed race/class combinations in EverQuest, so will it be in EverQuest II. During the character creation process you'll be shown the possible progression paths for whichever race you might be interested in.<BR>
<BR>
Races will have unique abilities, but none of them will be so unbalancing that it makes one race/class combo more desirable than any other. We intend to provide plenty of flavor and individuality without hurting the balance of the game.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> One of the main points of speculation is the class system. We know that there will be 48 classes, spread over 5 archetypes. Could you give us a brief overview of one never before revealed class?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Moorgard:</B> One class within the Scout archetype is called Predator. As the name implies, Predators are hunters, stalkers of prey. They use the abilities inherent to all classes within the Scout archetype-tracking their target, searching for and disarming traps, silently scouting ahead for enemy forces-to aid their party. They also do opportunistic damage to the big, bad monster while it's being distracted by a burly tank.<BR>
<BR>
Predators can ultimately become one of two sub-classes: Ranger or Assassin. While the implications of the Assassin are fairly straightforward, don't let the familiarity of the title "Ranger" fool you. The Ranger in EQ2 bears far more resemblance to how the class has been portrayed in fantasy literature than it does to the druid/warrior hybrid from the original EverQuest.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> Many titles are moving towards private zones to ease some problems. Will EverQuest II follow this mould? If so, how will it work? And if not, what will you do to prevent problems like the theft of quest monsters.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Moorgard:</B> EverQuest II will use the concept of private zones (often referred to as "instances") for a number of features. In terms of player housing, this allows individuals to have private apartments and houses that can be decorated to match their personal tastes. You will be able to decide who can enter your home and who can add items or move them around. In this way, instancing gives the individual player a lot of freedom to make a living area all their own.<BR>
<BR>
Some people have misconceptions about instanced encounters. Players will not be able to spawn their own ubermobs over and over at will; some encounters will have time restrictions (such as being spawnable once per week) while others will require a certain number of events to be completed before an instance can be entered. The idea is to ensure that content (whether it be certain raid mobs, quest mobs, etc.) that players plan for will be there, as long as they have done the required preparatory work beforehand.<BR>
<BR>
But instancing isn't just for high-level encounters. We can instance newbie areas so that players don't run out of things to kill, or we can create solo quests within instances. Basically, it's a tool that gives us a lot of freedom when designing content, but it's not something we plan to overuse in a way that would endanger the social aspects of the game.<div class=byline>-- <a href="mailto:lepidus@vaultnetwork.com">Lepidus</A></div>
